label.description: Here are entered works on people of French-Canadian birth or ancestry who are permanent residents of the United States, including naturalized citizens.
Here are entered works on Jewish Americans in the United States.

Here are entered works on competitive exhibitions of farm products, livestock, baked goods, etc. with prizes for excellence, often combined with carnival-like entertainment and held annually by states, counties, etc.
Here are entered works on clothing treated as an artistic object, as well as works on clothing created for the stage, screen, or special events.
Here are entered popular works on living in the country and works on manners and customs in rural areas.
Here are entered works discussing collectively the scientific disciplines which are basic to the practice of medicine and commonly covered in the preclinical years of the medical curriculum.

Here are entered works on people with disabilities as defined by the World Health Organization: "impairments, activity limitations, and participation restrictions. An impairment is a problem in body function or structure; an activity limitation is a difficulty encountered by an individual in executing a task or action; while a participation restriction is a problem experienced by an individual in involvement in life situations. Thus disability is a complex phenomenon, reflecting an interaction between features of a persons body and features of the society in which he or she lives" (NHF, 3/15/2010).
Here are entered works on organized efforts which seek to influence the decision making process within a specific group in relation to an election (NHF, 3/15/2010).

Here are entered works on types of open-pit mines from which rock or minerals are extracted and the extraction of said materials such as dimension stone, construction aggregate, riprap, sand, and gravel (NHF, 3/15/2010).
Here are entered works related to the farming, harvesting, and selling of blueberries in the state of Maine.

Here are entered general works on the activities and programs of missionaries and works on Christian missions. Works on the purpose of the church and its activities are entered under Mission of the church.
Here are entered works on commercial, private, and military airplanes including but not limited to: fighter planes, bombers, gliders and transport planes (NHF, 1/11/2011).
Short, unedited, silent films, primarily from the period of early cinema, that portray daily life or specific events or occurrences (MIGFG)

Work created by recording a series of still images, such as drawings, objects, or posed people; when played back, the static images combine to simulate motion, creating the impression of movement. (MIGFG) Also includes computer generated animation.
Produced especially for children as audience. (MIGFG) For works by children and students, see Student.
Documentary-style work that features dramatized re-enactments of actual events. (Wikipedia)
Nonfiction work...grounded in some aspect of real life. (MIGFG) See also Amateur.

Works intended to impart knowledge and information, including those for classroom viewing. Films that use a structured format to teach or train the audience are entered under Instructional films. (MIGFG)
Sexually oriented material that is not of an explicit nature. (MIGFG)
Usually originally released theatrically or direct to video, with an original length of at least forty minutes. (MIGFG)
Use for Dramatic-narrative films, entertainment films, fictional films. (MIGFG)

Work created for private, not commercial use, such as "home movies," designed to be shown primarily to family and friends, and usually made by people not professionally connected with the film-video industry. Does not include work by amateurs intended for public exhibition, or by independent filmmakers; such work should be treated the same as other theatrical product. (MIGFG) See also Independent.
Use for business films and industry-sponsored films. (MIGFG)
Works that use a structured format to teach or train the audience. Use Educational for works that are intended to impart knowledge and information, including those for classroom viewing. (MIGFG)

Nonfiction work of meeting between two or more persons, at least one of whose views and activities are elicited by means of questions asked and answered. Do not use for television news programs, panel shows or talk shows. (Nebraska State Historical Society)
Nonfiction work concentrating on the world of plants, insects, and animals, accounts of life in the wild, and how the ecosystems are formed... (MIGFG)
Nonfiction television relating topical events and background stories. (MIGFG)

Work that contains a variety of news footage, ranging in content from lifestyles to international events. Newsreels typically had a duration of about ten minutes in length and were released twice weekly to theaters in the United States from 1911-1967. (MIGFG)
Recording of historical information based on the personal experiences and opinions of the speaker. (Wikipedia) See also Interview
Excerpts from films and television programs usually excluded from the final versions of completed films or programs. (MIGFG)
Use for Campaign commercials, campaign spots, political spots (Television commercials). Broad term, Television commercials (Advertisements)
Recording of presentation by one or more speakers, which may be followed by questions from reporters. (Wikipedia)

Work that promotes or advertises a product, industry, service, organization, etc. Films produced, subsidized, financed, or otherwise significantly supported by a business, government body, organization, etc. are entered under Sponsored. (MIGFG)
Nonfiction work covering sporting events...the work may include the event itself, retrospective highlights, interviews with players, and commentary. (MIGFG)
Nonfiction work depicting travel, peoples, and places. (MIGFG) For travel by nonprofessional creators not intended for exhibition, use Amateur.
Footage recording an event or occasion. (MIGFG/NHF)
Films produced in the early days of the motion picture industry before the advent of talking films. (MIGFG)
Short piece made for television, paid for by the sellers of the product or services advertised, designed to be broadcast at breaks in television programs. (Nebraska State Historical Society)
Movie theater ads, pre-feature advertisements, theater ads (Motion pictures). (MIGFG) Advertising shown before movies in cinemas. (NHF)
A grouping of works, often on a single topic or theme. (NHF)
Work that seeks to expand traditional form, structure, and content. Used for Avant-garde. (MIGFG) See also Independent.

Work produced mostly outside of a major film studio. The term also refers to art films which differ markedly from most mass marketed films. Independent films are sometimes distinguishable by their content and style and the way in which the filmmakers' personal artistic vision is realized. (Wikipedia) See also Experimental. (NHF).
Fiction or nonfiction films that feature medical personnel and the practice of medicine. (MIGFG)

Nonfiction work documenting a performance, event, or concert ...Although the work being performed may be fictional, as with a stage play, the intent of the work in hand is documentation of that performance rather than a fictional narrative about it. (MIGFG) See also Unedited.
Television nonfiction work which include discussions, debates, speeches, and editorials on politics, government, and public policy. Used for Campaign; Debates; Editorial. (MIGFG)

A public service announcement (PSA) is an advertisement...intended to modify public attitudes by raising awareness about specific issues. The most common topics of PSAs are health and safety. A typical PSA is part of a public awareness campaign to inform or educate the public about an issue such as smoking or compulsive gambling....political campaign advertisements are not PSAs. (Wikipedia) (NHF)
Works usually limited to a running time of less than 40 minutes. (MIGFG) To be used generally for fiction works and those not falling under amateur, independent, or other more specific genres. (NHF)

Work produced, subsidized, financed, or otherwise significantly supported by a business, government body, organization, etc. Films that promote or advertise a product, industry, service, organization, etc. are entered under Promotional films. (MIGFG) See also Industrial.
Fiction or nonfiction work created by young people from Kindergarten through college. (NHF)
Use for films created for local exhibition, usually by itinerant filmmakers in small cities and towns, capturing as many individuals as possible.

Films dependent upon extensive use of "trick photography" or special effects such as stop motion, fast or slow motion, dissolves, and multiple exposures (MIGFG). Amateur and student works employing effects such as running the film backward and stop motion for comic or mysterious effect (NHF).

About OCLC : Public Purpose Public Purpose
Furthering access to the world's information and reducing the rate of rise of per-unit costs
OCLC is a worldwide library cooperative, owned, governed and sustained by members since 1967. Our public purpose is a statement of commitment to each otherthat we will work together to improve access to the information held in libraries around the globe, and find ways to reduce costs for libraries through collaboration.
Our public purpose is to establish, maintain and operate a computerized library network and to promote the evolution of library use, of libraries themselves and of librarianship, and to provide processes and products for the benefit of library users and libraries, including such objectives as increasing availability of library resources to individual library patrons and reducing the rate-of-rise of library per-unit costs, all for the fundamental public purpose of furthering ease of access to and use of the ever-expanding body of worldwide scientific, literary and educational knowledge and information.

label.name: Description
label.description: The metadata element description uses free-form text or a narrative to report general notes, abstracts, or summaries about the intellectual content of a media item you are cataloging. The information may be in the form of a paragraph giving an individual program description, anecdotal interpretations, or brief content reviews. The description may also consist of outlines, lists, bullet points, rundowns, segment sequence, edit decision lists, indexes, or tables of content.

label.name: Temporal coverage
label.description: Enter a date/time or range of date/times. You can be a specific (eg. 07/14/2001 @ 10:54:01am) or as general (circa 2001) as required.

label.name: Spatial coverage
label.description: Enter an address or locality name. Your input will be converted automatically to map coordinates.

label.name: Identifier (pbcore)
label.description: Each NHF IC record should only have 1 identifier. This Identifier (pbcore) field was created only for the migration of ProCite records. New IC records should not have any data in the Identifier (pbcore) field, only the Identifier field, and all records containing data there must be cleaned up (data moved into the correct identifier field and the Identifier (pbcore) field delete.

label.name: Subject
label.description: The descriptor subject is used to assign topical headings or keywords that portray the intellectual content of the media item you are cataloging. Typically, a subject is expressed by a limited number of keywords, key phrases, or even specific classification codes.

label.name: Genre
label.description: The descriptor genre describes the manner in which the intellectual content of a media item is presented, viewed or heard by a user. It indicates the structure of the presentation, as well as the topical nature of the content in a generalized form.

label.name: Relation
label.description: The descriptor relationType identifies the type of intellectual content bond between a media item you are cataloging and some other related media item. Once the type of relationship between two media items is identified by using the descriptor relationType, then this companion descriptor relationIdentifier is used to provide a name, locator, accession, identification number or ID where the related item can be obtained or found. The cross reference uses a unique identifier.

label.name: Audience Level
label.description: The descriptor audienceLevel identifies a type of audience, viewer, or listener for whom the media item you are cataloging is primarily designed or educationally useful.

label.name: Audience Rating
label.description: The descriptor audienceRating designates the type of users for whom a media item is intended or judged appropriate in terms of its intellectual content. Standard ratings have been crafted by the broadcast television and film industries and are used as flags for audience or age-appropriate materials.

label.name: Rights Summary
label.description: Information about rights held in and over the resource.

label.name: Date Created
label.description: Use the descriptor dateCreated to specify the creation date for a particular version or rendition of a media item across its life cycle. It is the moment in time that the media item was finalized during its production process and is forwarded to other divisions or agencies to make it ready for publication or distribution.

label.name: Date Issued
label.description: The descriptor dateIssued specifies the formal date for a particular version or rendition of a media item has been made ready or officially released for distribution, publication or consumption.

label.name: Format: Location
label.description: Document the physical location of the instantiation here. Examples: CME2, MCG6, Blue Hill Vault, smb://nhfnas001/video/xpost_August_2008_cataloged/nhf-0853_0145

label.name: Media Type
label.description: The descriptor formatMediaType identifies the general, high level nature of the content of a media item. It uses categories that show how content is presented to an observer, e.g., as a sound or text or moving image.

label.name: Format: Generations Types for Moving Images
Format: Generations Types for Moving Images
Format: Generations Types for Static Images
Format: Generations Types for Static Images
Format: Standard
label.description: Use the descriptor formatStandard to identify a larger technical system/standard or overarching media architecture under which various media formats exist, e.g., NTSC is a system/standard under which many video formats exist.

label.name: Format: Encoding
label.description: The descriptor formatEncoding identifies how the actual information in a media item is compressed, interpreted, or formulated using a particular scheme. Identifying the encoding used is beneficial for a number of reasons, including as a way to achieve reversible compression; for the construction of document indices to facilitate searching and access; or for efficient distribution of the information across data networks with differing bandwidths or pipeline capacities.

label.name: Format: Sampling Rate
label.description: For a media item (specifically audio), the descriptor formatSamplingRate measures "How Often " data is sampled when information is digitized. For a digital audio signal, the sampling rate is measured in kiloHertz and is an indicator of the perceived playback quality of the media item (the higher the sampling rate, the greater the fidelity).

label.name: Format: Frame Size
label.description: he descriptor formatFrameSize indicates the horizontal and vertical resolution of a format type. It may be expressed in pixels, pixels per inch, or in the case of ATSC digital TV, a combination of pixels measured horizontally vs. the number of pixels of image/resolution data stacked vertically (interlaced and progressive scan).

label.name: Format: Aspect Ratio
label.description: The descriptor formatAspectRatio indicates the ratio of horizontal to vertical proportions in the display of an static image or moving image.

label.name: Format: Frame Rate
label.description: The descriptor formatFrameRate indicates the frames per second found in a video, motion sequence, flash file, or animation's playback or display.

label.name: Format: Tracks
label.description: The descriptor formatTracks is simply intended to indicate the number and type of tracks that are found in a media item, whether it is analog or digital.

label.name: Collection summary
label.description:
"DACS 3.1 Scope and Content: First sentence: A statement listing the physical contents of the collection (including reels of film, published books, film equipment whatever is accessioned into the collection), including creator and creation dates. Next 3-4 sentences: Statements highlighting the main topics, events, locations, people, etc. within the collection. Last sentence: End the paragraph with a statement highlighting the most important or significant items in the collection. If there arent any specific dates, places or people, then make a general statement about what makes the collection significant a final statement aimed at potential researchers.
This element provides information about the nature of the materials and activities reflected in the unit being described to enable users to judge its potential relevance. See additional rules in Chapter 3.1 for details."

label.name: Biographical and historical notes
label.description: "DACS 10.0 Administrative/Biographical History: The purpose of this element is to provide information about the organization(s) or individual(s) associated in some way with the creation, assembly, accumulation, and/or maintenance and use of the unit being described in order to place the material in context and make it better understood. See additional rules in Chapter 10 for details."

role.description: A cataloger can search, browse, create, edit and delete records. They can also create and manage search forms, displays and sets.

role.name: intern
role.description: An intern can search, browse, and create and edit records, but cannot delete records

role.name: Researcher
role.description: A researcher can search and browse the records but cannot edit anything.

group.name: Intern
group.description: This group is for the lowest level of access for the NHF collection catalog.
